                                                        <div class="item-page">

	<h2>
			<a href="/index.php/79-python-resources/117-nested-lists">
		Nested Lists</a>
		</h2>








<p><strong>By Alissa Powers</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><br />#ICS32</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">## Manipulating Nested Lists</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">## Imagine the following scenario:<br />##&nbsp; A room is a number of guests staying in a room of a hotel. A floor is a list of rooms. For a given hotel, there is a list of floors in the hotel containing lists of rooms on the floor. The numbers in these lists add up to the total number of guests staying in the hotel. (note: The number of floors and the number of rooms on a floor are given as variables, considering that the building size will not change during our calculation.)</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">##&nbsp; Example:<br />##&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We are given the following information about a hotel.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; NUMBER_OF_FLOORS = 4<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; NUMBER_OF_ROOMS = 3<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; NUMBER_OF_GUESTS = [[3, 3, 1],[2, 4, 2],[1, 4, 3],[2, 2, 2]]<br />##&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (note: NUMBER_OF_GUESTS is a list of floors. Each entry within NUMBER_OF_GUESTS is a floor, which is a&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; list of rooms. Each room in each floor is just a number representing the number of guests staying in that room.)</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">##&nbsp; We want our program to print out the floor numbers from lowest to highest and then the number of guests in each room on that floor beneath the floor number, with the total number of guests on that floor at the very bottom. The example output for the above data is:</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">##&nbsp;&nbsp; 1&nbsp;&nbsp; 2&nbsp;&nbsp; 3&nbsp;&nbsp; 4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &lt;- these are the floors<br />##&nbsp; |3| |2| |1| |2|&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &lt;- these are the numbers of guests in each floor<br />##&nbsp; |3| |4| |4| |2|<br />##&nbsp; |1| |2| |3| |2|<br />##&nbsp; ---------------<br />##&nbsp;&nbsp; 7&nbsp;&nbsp; 8&nbsp;&nbsp; 8&nbsp;&nbsp; 6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &lt;- these are the total number of guests on each floor</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">## We want this program to work regardless of the given input. We should be able to use this on any hotel, as long as they give the right information (i.e. NUMBER_OF_FLOORS, etc.)<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">## PART A<br />## First we would print out the floor numbers with the proper spacing. So we would make a string and add the numbers to it.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">floors_to_print = ''<br />for number in range(NUMBER_OF_FLOORS):<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; floors_to_print += ' ' + str(number+1) + '&nbsp; '<br />print(floors_to_print)</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><br />##&nbsp; PART B<br />##&nbsp; Note that we cannot print downwards and then return to the top to print more in the shell. We need to print everything we want across and move downwards. To do this, we need to print out each item of the lists by index. So we want to go through the NUMBER_OF_GUESTS list and print index 0 from each room within NUMBER_OF_GUESTS and then print index 1 from each room and so on. So we would again make a string for proper formatting and then loop through the lists and add the numbers to the string.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">for room in range(NUMBER_OF_ROOMS):<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; guests_to_print = ''<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; for floor in range(NUMBER_OF_FLOORS):<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; guests_to_print += '|' + str(NUMBER_OF_GUESTS[floor][room]) + '| '<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; print(guests_to_print)</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">##&nbsp; Another option would be to change the second for loop so that NUMBER_OF_GUESTS does not need to be doubly indexed. Try commenting out the code above and uncommenting the code below and then running the program. The output should be the same.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">##for room in range(NUMBER_OF_ROOMS):<br />##&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; guests_to_print = ''<br />##&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; for floor in NUMBER_OF_GUESTS:<br />##&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; guests_to_print += '|' + str(floor[room]) + '| '<br />##&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; print(guests_to_print)</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">##PART C<br />##&nbsp; Printing the total calculations is easy, although to format it properly we need to use the same sort of structure as part A.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">totals_to_print = ''<br />dashed_line = ''</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">for x in range(NUMBER_OF_FLOORS):<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; dashed_line += "----"<br />print(dashed_line[1:])</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">for floor in NUMBER_OF_GUESTS:<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; total_guests_per_floor = 0<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; for room in floor:<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; total_guests_per_floor += room<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; totals_to_print += ' ' + str(total_guests_per_floor) + '&nbsp; '<br />print(totals_to_print)</p> 
	
</div>


